= ValeciumOS Implementation Roadmap
:toc: left
:icons: font

See also: link:index.html[Home], link:devel.html[Developer Guide]

== Current Status

Valecium OS is at version 0.28. The i686 BIOS path boots, initializes core subsystems, mounts a FAT root filesystem, and launches userspace processes. The custom bootloader has stage1 (MBR) and stage2 (protected mode entry) but does not yet load the kernel — GRUB is the current boot method.

== Short-Term Todo

* [ ] Ext2 filesystem driver (enum exists, no implementation)
* [ ] FAT LFN (Long File Name) support
* [ ] ATAPI and ISO9660 optical drive support
* [ ] Signal delivery mechanism and signal syscall completion
* [ ] Smart heap allocation that actually frees memory
* [ ] Make kernel PIC & PIE
* [ ] Kernel partition filesystem detection (not just partition ID)
* [ ] Memory protection (read/write/execute permissions)
* [ ] Complete custom bootloader (stage2 loads kernel)

== Phase 1: Core OS Infrastructure

=== Memory Management

* [x] Physical Memory Manager (PMM) — page frame allocation
* [x] Virtual Memory Manager (VMM) — paging, per-process address spaces
* [x] Kernel heap (kmalloc/kfree/kzalloc/calloc/realloc)
* [x] Per-process heap (brk/sbrk syscalls)
* [x] Stack management (per-process user stacks)
** [x] Refactor user stack allocation (move from process.c to stack.c)
** [x] Implement `Stack_CreateUser` using PMM/Paging (not kmalloc)
** [x] Map user-mode exit trampoline (fix GPF on return)
** [x] Update TSS ESP0 on context switch
* [ ] Memory protection (read/write/execute permissions)
* [x] Page tables and MMU setup
* [x] Kernel virtual memory layout (3 GB / 1 GB split)

=== Process Management

* [x] Process Control Block (PCB) structure
* [ ] Process creation & destroy (fork/execve syscalls)
** [x] Add Kernel Stack to Process Struct
** [x] Allocate Kernel Stack in Process_Create
** [x] Free Kernel Stack in Process_Destroy
** [x] Set Parent PID
** [ ] Initialize Standard File Descriptors (stdin, stdout, stderr)
** [x] Handle Arguments (argv/envp)
** [x] Scheduler Registration
* [x] Process scheduling & context switching (basic round-robin)
* [x] Process termination (exit syscall)
* [x] Fork implementation (Process_Clone)
* [x] Exec implementation (Process_Execute)
* [ ] Signal handling (signal syscalls)
* [ ] User-mode ring 3 execution
* [x] Kernel-mode execution
* [x] Credentials (uid/gid/euid/egid per process)
* [ ] User/kernel mode switching

=== Filesystem

* [x] FAT12/16/32 filesystem read/write
* [x] FAT_Create() — create new files
* [x] FAT_Delete() — delete files
* [x] FAT_Truncate() — truncate files
* [x] Multi-cluster file support (files > 1 cluster)
* [x] Device filesystem (devfs) — /dev/tty0, /dev/null, /dev/zero
* [x] Virtual Filesystem Switch (VFS) — open/read/write/seek/close/dispatch
* [x] File descriptors table per process (16 entries)
* [x] Disk abstraction layer (MBR/VBR parsing, partitions)
* [ ] FAT_Stat() — file metadata
* [ ] Ext2 filesystem driver
* [x] FAT directory operations (readdir, create dir entry)

=== Terminal Support

* [x] TTY driver for `/dev/tty0`
* [x] Terminal line discipline (buffering, echo control)
* [x] ANSI escape sequence support
* [x] Keyboard input handling (platform-independent dispatcher)
* [x] Terminal control ioctl calls
* [x] Canonical/raw mode switching
* [x] Line editing (backspace, CTRL+C/D/U/W/Z)

== Phase 2: Syscalls Wrappers

=== File I/O Syscalls

* [x] `read` — read from file descriptor
* [x] `write` — write to file descriptor
* [x] `open` — open file
* [x] `close` — close file descriptor
* [x] `lseek` — seek in file
* [x] `chmod` — change file mode (stub)
* [x] `chown` — change file ownership (stub)
* [ ] `fstat`, `stat`, `lstat` — file metadata
* [ ] `ioctl` — device control
* [ ] `fcntl` — file control
* [ ] `access` — check permissions

=== Memory Syscalls

* [x] `brk` — set data segment size (for malloc)
* [x] `sbrk` — increment data segment size
* [ ] `mmap`, `munmap` — memory mapping
* [ ] `mprotect` — set memory protection
* [ ] `mremap` — remap memory region

=== Process Syscalls

* [x] `exit` — process termination
* [x] `fork` — process creation
* [x] `execve` — execute program
* [x] `getpid` — get process ID
* [x] `getppid` — get parent process ID
* [x] `getuid` — get user ID
* [x] `setuid` — set user ID
* [x] `getgid` — get group ID
* [x] `setgid` — set group ID
* [x] `wait4` — wait for child process
* [ ] `exit_group` — exit all threads in group
* [ ] `clone` — create thread

=== Signal Syscalls

* [ ] `signal`, `sigaction` — signal handlers (partial: sigaction.c exists)
* [ ] `sigprocmask`, `sigpending` — signal masking (partial: sigprocmask.c exists)
* [ ] `kill` — send signal (partial: kill.c exists)
* [ ] `pause` — wait for signal
* [ ] `alarm` — timer signal
* [ ] `sigreturn` — return from signal handler (arch stub exists)

Note: Signal infrastructure files exist (`kernel/signal/` and `kernel/arch/i686/signal/`) but core signal delivery is not fully integrated with the scheduler and process lifecycle.

=== Time Syscalls

* [ ] `time` — current time
* [ ] `gettimeofday`, `clock_gettime` — precise time
* [ ] `nanosleep` — sleep
* [ ] `select`, `poll` — I/O multiplexing

=== Miscellaneous Syscalls

* [ ] `uname` — system info
* [ ] `getpagesize` — page size
* [ ] `prctl` — process control
* [ ] `umask` — file creation mask
* [ ] `nice`, `getpriority`, `setpriority` — scheduling

== Phase 3: Advanced Features

=== Device Support

* [x] `/dev/null` device file
* [x] `/dev/zero` device file
* [x] Device node mounting (devfs)
* [ ] `/dev/random`, `/dev/urandom` — entropy source
